Jeremy Corbyn to debut on Prime Minister's Questions
Since his election, Mr. Corbyn's PMQ debut has been highly anticipated.
New Labour leader Jeremy Corbyn will make his debut in Prime Minister's Questions later, and will have his first collaboration with David Cameron.
Mr Corbyn will pose the first of his six allocated questions shortly after noon, while his performance is likely to be scrutinised by the media and Members.
In a weekly statement, he asked for “less theatre and more facts.”
He also said he might skip a few sessions that he would leave to his colleagues.
This meeting will be the first parliamentary test of Mr Corby’s leadership, which comes after his appointment to the shadow cabinet and his Tuesday speech to the annual TUC Congress.
Meanwhile, the Labour leader’s decision to stand in silence while singing the national anthem in service on Tuesday to mark the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Britain has met with criticism from a number of Conservative MPs and is the focus of several front-page stories.
Mr Corbyn's decision not to sing the national anthem has drawn attention.
A spokesman for Mr Corbyn said he would "stand in respectful silence" and would recognise "the heroism of the Royal Air Force in the Battle of Britain."
But Mr Corbyn’s shadow cabinet member, Owen Smith, told BBC Two’s Newsnight programme that he would recommend the Labour leader sing the national anthem “regardless” of his belief that the monarchy should be abolished.
Nearly a dozen shadow ministers refused to serve on Mr Corbyn’s top team, citing differences in the economy, defense and foreign affairs, and only less than a sixth of the parliamentary party initially supported him as leader.
BBC political correspondent Robin Brant says political differences in the workplace are also "collapsed" after Mr Corbyn's appointment despite his position in the European Union and the government's limit on benefits.
Mr Corbyl told the TUC conference that the Workers' Party had tabled amended proposals to remove the whole idea of the benefit limit.
A few hours later, Mr Smith, the secretary of shadow work and pensions, said the party had "very clearly" opposed government plans to reduce the limit from <0xC2><0xA3>26,000 to <0xC2><0xA3>23,000.
Mr Corbyn will be the fifth Labour leader to face David Cameron in the decade since his election as Conservative leader.
The Labour leader, who has promised a different approach to politics, says he has ideas “from the crowd” on questions for Mr Cameron and has received more than 30,000 proposals.
MP Islington North argues that PMQ is too confrontational and that it will refrain from both "quick answers" and toothed trade, and instead promises to focus on important issues such as poverty, inequality and the challenges facing young people.
Mr Corbyn says Angela Eagle, the shadow trade secretary, will represent him at PMQ if he does not attend — such as when Mr Cameron travels abroad.
He also dropped the idea of letting other colleagues speak for him from time to time because he was told that he had still discussed the matter with House Speaker John Bercow.
When Mr Cameron became leader in 2005, he said he wanted to move away from the "Punch and Judy" style of politics that was often associated with PMQ, but admitted years later that it had failed.
Since its first broadcast in 1990, PMQ has been seen as a key barometer of leaders' judgment, their leadership of the House, and their attitude among other MPs, although critics have argued that it has become a caricature and that far-reaching reforms are needed.
