Multiple sclerosis: it is not only the drugs that matter, but also the patient’s will to fight.
Multiple sclerosis is a complicated disease, and a person with this diagnosis needs the care of a number of specialists: a neurologist, a physiotherapist, an occupational therapist, a urologist, an ophthalmologist, a psychologist, a psychiatrist and many other specialists.
However, it is not only about medical care, for example, women with multiple sclerosis also need consultations, if they decide to have a child, the care of these patients includes social and legal advice, recommendations for the adjustment of housing, etc.
Yet all this is not enough: the development of the disease can significantly affect the patient himself.
The more he actively fights the disease, the longer he can work and does not have to fundamentally change his lifestyle.
As doctors point out, the passivity of patients frees up space for the activity of the disease.
For example, regular exercise has been shown to significantly delay the time the patient needs some kind of compensatory aid, such as a staff.
It is important that patients and their surroundings are not subject to various myths, for example, that the disease automatically leads them to end up in a wheelchair.
That is why we created the Give Yourself a Chance page (www.bezmytu.cz), which is supported by the ongoing media campaign Give Yourself a Chance.
The most important person in the care of a patient with multiple sclerosis is a neurologist.
With multiple sclerosis, it is said twice that the sooner the disease is treated, the more likely the doctor can influence something.
This is because we have drugs for multiple sclerosis in the inflammatory stage, when the process of neurodegeneration is not yet so strong.
The sooner we intervene, the greater the hope that we will be able to stop the disease and delay the disability, explains Dr. Eva Medová from the Neurology Clinic of the General University Hospital in Prague.
It is very important for people with multiple sclerosis rehabilitation care, which most often addresses the weakening of the lower limbs or balance disorders.
Patients are treated according to their individual needs: to maintain fitness, improve walking, strengthen the pelvic floor, relieve swallowing disorders or improve coordination.
"It's really individual, it depends on the specific difficulties of the patient," says MUDr. Martina K<0xC3><0xB6>vári, head of the Department of Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine at the University Hospital in Motol.
People with multiple sclerosis suffer from the same disease, but it manifests itself in a slightly different way for everyone.
Rehabilitation can not stop the disease, but it can always relieve its symptoms.
However, physical activity also strengthens the immune state of the body, which is desirable in the case of multiple sclerosis.
Another positive of regular exercise is the fact that the sick check what they can do, and this strengthens their self-confidence.
"Endorphins are also flushed out during exercise and one feels good after it," notes PhDr. Kamila <0xC5><0x98>asová from the Clinic of Rehabilitation Medicine of the University Hospital of Královské Vinohrady.
By influencing the physical side, we act on the limbic system responsible for emotions.
This directly interferes with the psyche and immune processes and stabilizes the disease, he adds.
"Previously, these patients were so-called savings, today we know that they need a targeted load," says Prof. PaedDr. Pavel Kolá<0xC5><0x99>, head of the Department of Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine at the Motol University Hospital.
The goal of physiotherapy is that a person can remain self-sufficient for as long as possible, including work placement.
Therefore, physiotherapists work with occupational therapists to ensure that each person receives a compensation aid tailored to them.
Many patients also need the care of a psychologist or psychiatrist.
They are in a difficult life situation.
When a serious illness comes into your life, most people shake it up.
They experience shock, panic, fear.
They must respond to a great burden - loss of health.
With such a sore soul, we have to go to someone, not try to bear everything on our own shoulders.
"I work with them to finally come to the conclusion that even with a disability you can live a full life and that multiple sclerosis does not mean the end of life," says psychotherapist Renata Malinová-Schubertová from the Neurology Clinic of the General University Hospital in Prague.
