“Sonogenetics” or control of brain cells using sound waves
This video shows how sound impulses affect the direction in which the nematodes move.
Scientists have grown worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can control sound waves.
Small nematodes change direction when they are struck by sound impulses that are inaudible to the human ear.
Pulses work by switching the cells of genetically modified motor neurons that are programmed to respond to these ultrasound waves.
Scientists can read and record brain activity using light
The researchers said the worms are a great example of a new technique called sonogenetics, which uses ultrasound to activate brain, heart and muscle cells and activates outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told the Guardian that this method could one day replace deep brain stimulation — an invasive procedure in which electrodes that stimulate the brain are inserted into the patient’s brain. The method is used, for example, to treat symptoms of Parkinson’s disease.
The nematodes usually do not respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that the reaction occurs when they are placed in a liquid containing microscopic bubbles.
As he found out, the bubbles are amplified by ultrasound waves, which then pass through the body of worms.
The amplified ultrasonic waves act in the TRP-4 ion channels, which are found in the membranes of some worm cells.
These channels open up and activate the cells with which they are connected, according to a report in the journal Nature Communications.
In order to control the nematodes using ultrasound waves, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their motor neurons contained TRP-4 ion channels.
When he then applied ultrasound to the modified worms, the sound waves were amplified by microbubbles and transferred to the worms, where they turned on the modified motor neurons.
The new method is in many ways similar to optogenetics, a pioneering tool that allows scientists to turn neurons on and off using light.
Chalasani, however, made it clear that sonogenetics could have many advantages over this technique.
Unlike light, which must be sent by an optical fiber to the desired location in the brain, ultrasound waves can penetrate tissues without restriction and be sent directly to the brain.
