No one has explained to me how I should keep refugees in the country if they do not want to live in the Czech Republic.
Czech Interior Minister Milan Chovanec (<0xC4><0x8C>SSD), after talks with his European colleagues, complains that other Czech states are pushing for the adoption of quotas for the redistribution of refugees, but they reject any discussion.
He also notes that no one has yet explained to him how he should keep assigned refugees in the Czech Republic, if they do not want to live here anyway.
"We did not receive an answer, so we wanted the quotas to be removed from the final text," Chovanec told reporters.
Can you describe in more concrete terms the position that you have taken at the meetings of the Ministers of the Interior and Foreign Affairs of the European Union?
We do not agree with mandatory quotas as a system that simply cannot work.
We cannot talk about migrants as bags of salt or flour.
They are living beings who have visions, they are going somewhere, they have relatives.
We wanted to hear from our colleagues how we would be able to keep migrants on the territory of the Member States if they were to be redistributed.
We can't imagine.
We did not receive an answer, so we wanted the quotas to be deleted from the final text.
With the other conclusions - functional hotspots, i.e. registration points, border protection, camps outside Europe, the trust fund for African countries and other things, we have no problem with that.
We've been talking about this for a year, and we're saying this is the way.
But to say that quotas will solve everything?
We've dealt with forty thousand before, now it's one hundred and twenty thousand.
When will it be five hundred thousand?
And how do we keep these people in the area?
Ninety-eight percent of the people who cross us want to go to Germany.
Almost no one wants us, we just don't know how to keep them here.
Other foreigners, Ukrainians, Vietnamese and others, who take the Czech Republic as a destination country, receive asylum in our country, have ambitions to come to us, but the interest of people from this migration wave, that is, from Syria and other countries, is limited to close to zero.
You mentioned that the refugees don’t even want to come to us, but we have already committed to admit fifteen hundred people.
Would it not be possible to receive more of them in this way?
We are committed to taking in 1,500 people, but with a condition.
We said: functional hotspots, border protection, military operation.
Even for the 1500, the point is that there will be 1,100 people with whom we will deal with the asylum procedure.
They'll come to our detention facility and we'll treat them the same way we did the ones we caught.
It is a big question, and we will debate this with Europe, whether we can detain people who will be registered in Italy and in Greece or in Hungary.
Because Europe is behaving in such a way that if they have a registration, they cannot be detained.
That is, they will come to our territory with registration, and if there is an agreement that is not yet there, it may happen that we will not keep even the 1100 in the Czech Republic and they will leave for Germany again upon arrival.
If we can detain them for the duration of the asylum procedure, we will handle the asylum procedure with them.
If they are citizens of Syria, Eritrea, almost 98 percent of them receive international protection, according to European statistics.
Then they will receive documents that will allow them to travel around Europe.
And I think these people will end up in the target countries again.
Then there are four hundred people who will be resettled.
This is the second project that is still underway, and we have only advanced there by debating with the churches about the possibility that they could help them find jobs, housing, and so on.
But that's a long run.
You said that the other countries were not willing to discuss with us at the ministerial meeting.
But is it not the case that the Czech Republic only rejects quotas, but does not offer any solidarity step that would unblock the discussion?
And what exactly do you think this solidarity step should be?
If the Federal Republic of Germany gives an incentive that all migrants from Syria can come to them, the message spreads in hours across all camps in Europe, but also in Turkey, Jordan.
It triggers another wave of migration that is heading to Germany because they just don’t want to come to us.
We think that the way is to protect the external borders - simply to discourage those migration waves, to help the needy, and to separate economic migrants.
Make it clear to them that they don’t have a chance.
Last year alone, 50,000 Kosovars came to Germany.
From a safe Kosovo, where we pay for all the saturation of that state, including the police, the courts, the prosecutor’s offices.
If we could separate them and not accept them, or accept them only according to the needs of the economies, the fifty percent of what the social systems spend on them today in vain could go to refugees.
Compared to the first day when Germany introduced controls, the number of detainees in the Czech Republic jumped.
Now it's eighty, the first day it was twelve.
How far will it go to tighten border controls?
We were afraid of being caught by hundreds of people.
These are the numbers we can handle.
We still have several hundred free places in stone detention facilities.
Of course, all the people we detain will be returned to Austria within seven days.
We do it by default.
The Austrians are the only ones who take these people away from us, it is complicated with Hungary and the Greeks - this is a completely unnecessary story.
So where is the breaking point?
Would it have to be a thousand a day?
I think it would have to be a few hundred a day.
Two hundred, three hundred people a day, two, three days in a row, they're going to run out of capacity for us to make contingency plans.
Then I have agreed with the Prime Minister to convene an extraordinary government immediately.
He is very interested in the whole thing, we are in telephone contact several times a day.
Should this situation arise, the government can sit down de facto immediately and, in one resolution, it would decide to strengthen the police with the army, let’s say the customs administration, or possibly with the prison service.
The extreme variant is the state of emergency that Hungary has now declared in some places?
I don't think it can come this far.
Remember that our position is different, we are a national state within Europe, we have the Schengen border only and only at the airport.
I do not know what would have to happen for this to happen on the territory of the Czech Republic, I do not want to spread alarmist information.
All the information we have, whether from Moldova, Serbia, Hungary, suggests rather that the Hungarians will try to divert the migration flow to Croatia and Slovenia, which would then mean a direct route to Austria.
The Czech Republic would be affected very marginally, almost at all.
