At its most anticipated session in years, the Federal Reserve lawmakers will spend two days sitting at the 27-foot-long Honduran mahogany table this week, deciding whether, after nearly a decade, the time has come to raise the key interest rate.
Rising above them at one end of the central bank ornament, the two-story meeting room will be a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues are supposed to put the nation’s economic interests above everything else.
The central bank has a double congressional charge: maximize U.S. employment and keep prices stable.
But since the Great Recession, Fed officials have acknowledged that there is an unwritten third term: financial stability.
And this third term could be an X-factor in too close to a predictable decision to be announced on Thursday on whether the U.S. economy is ready to run when weaned from an unprecedented stimulus in the form of near-zero short-term interest rates on the spot by the end of 2008.
Although most of the data shows solid economic growth, recent turbulence in global financial markets could scare the already cautious Fed into adding to the volatility by raising its federal funds reference rate — no more than a quarter of a percentage point.
“Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the most important thing to watch out for,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think they were just looking for an excuse not to increase the rate, the increased uncertainty surrounding the global market already provides them with sufficient justification to wait any longer,” she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself causes nervousness in the financial markets.
About half of economists recently polled by Blomberg predicted a rate hike this week.
However, financial markets expect the Fed to delay the matter, with a key indicator of only about 30% of the chances of an increase.
This would point to a decline in the stock market if the Fed raised rates only if politicians softened the decline by promising that further increases were not forthcoming.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average jumped 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The rally was triggered by the expectation that Fed policymakers will hold rates steady this week, says John Lonski, chief economist at Moody’s Capital Markets Research Group.
“It would be a surprise if the Fed raised rates now,” he said.
If the Fed did, “they would have to go to the extreme in their program statement and hold the financial markets in their hands to avoid panic.”
Other experts argued that raising rates would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about how the Fed would proceed.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed well on its way to raising the rate by 0.25 percentage point this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the US economic recovery.
Yellen said she expects rates to rise this year through spring and early summer, despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress is needed.
While job creation slowed in August, the labour market has seen solid growth this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% in the previous month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to what the Fed considers full employment.
Wage gains showed signs of lift.
And while inflation continues to fall below the central bank’s annual 2% target, Fed policymakers say the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy "can cope with higher rates and needs them, given the tightness of the labor market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world began to shake at the end of last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell as much as 16% below its record value in May, as investors feared that China’s slowing economy would drag global growth down.
The market has rebounded somewhat this month and the Dow is now losing only nearly 10% of its May high.
To the Fed’s policymakers, the market turmoil provides a complex calculus of when to start raising interest rates.
“In the absence of what has happened in the financial markets, and reports of the weakness of the Chinese economy over the past few weeks, there would be tightening at this meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, lead researcher at UCLA’s Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Fed official.
Now he predicts they will wait at least a month to gain better control over the consequences.
“There is a lot of uncertainty about the impact this will have on the U.S. economy, and they have almost no data to rely on about the latest developments in China,” Oliner said.
The health of the global economy is not one of the Fed’s main interests, so technically it should not be included in their decision-making.
But in reality, the Fed has become the monetary authority of the whole world.
The central bank’s influence in recent years has been enormous.
The mere hint by then-Chairman Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could “narrow down” their monetary expansion in the market has triggered convulsions around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly interconnected, Fed officials can be expected to follow developments elsewhere, but also consult with other central bankers and experts to better read the state of the global economy.
Their decision-making process is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of global wealth-management strategy at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., noted this month that “the Fed has a history of exaggerating with movements in financial markets that seem unrelated to economic fundamentals.”
Lacker, a voting policy-making member of the Federal Open Market Committee who pushed for rate hikes, cited the 1998-99 decision as an example.
The financial crisis in Asia led the Fed to cut its benchmark rate by 0.75 percentage points over three sessions “despite the limited identifiable impact on U.S. growth,” Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials reversed those cuts.
The Fed should prioritize financial stability concerns only during a major crisis such as the 2008 market crash, said Adam Posen S., a former member of the rate-setting committee at the Bank of England.
The latest uproar is not even close to that level, he said.
“You certainly don’t want to be in a situation of fear of rising rates because the markets are getting angry,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act has a dual mandate and does not mention financial stability, and until that changes, I do not think they should be at the top.
