For Slightly Obese Diabetics, Weight Loss Surgery Could Be Helpful
The benefits of weight loss surgery for slightly obese people with type 2 diabetes can last at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is too early to say whether mildly obese people with type 2 diabetes live longer after weight loss surgery than those who are given non-surgical treatment.
“The mortality data takes a long time to show,” says Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in weight loss surgery who wrote an editorial for the new JAMA surgery study.
Surgery for weight loss, bariatric surgery use different methods to shrink the stomach.
Reducing hunger and limiting the human body to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has been shown to be effective for the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but most of the research was done on people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) of 25 or higher.
The BMI, which measures the weight-to-height ratio, is considered normal at values between 18.5 and 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or higher indicates overweight and people over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For their new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected from a 2007 study that looked at two types of bariatric surgery — gastric bypass surgery and gastrectomy — in the treatment of type 3 diabetes in people who were mildly obese.
The average BMI among those who underwent surgery fell from 31 to 24.5 by the end of their fifth year, according to the study.
Meanwhile, the BMI of those who were not given surgical treatment for diabetes remained roughly the same at 29.
Among patients with surgery, diabetes was completely resolved in 36 percent and partially in 28 cases.
In the drug-treated group, for comparison, diabetes was completely resolved in only 1 percent and partially only in about 2 percent of patients.
In addition, control of blood pressure, triglycerides, and “bad” LDL cholesterol was shown to be “generally better in the surgical group,” the authors found.
The researchers also monitored the patient’s hemoglobin A1c levels in the blood, which reflect ongoing blood sugar levels in the body.
Hemoglobin A1c is best kept below 7 percent, the researchers said.
After surgery, the average hemoglobin A1c decreased from about 9 percent to about 6 percent.
In the drug-treated group, however, this value remained at about 8 percent.
But this better “glycemic control” — which is reflected in better hemoglobin A1c levels — did not reduce mortality in five years, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and his colleagues.
The research team also compared average results with two types of operations.
After the fifth year, the bypass group lost more weight compared to the gastrectomy group (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), achieved greater decreases in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1 percent versus 2.1 percent), and were more likely to be in remission of diabetes (46.9 versus 16.7 percent).
While the new study shows no improvement in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of stronger people in Sweden where they found that surgery leads to longer life, says Blackstone of the University of Arizona College or Medicine-Phoenix.
According to a Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery had about a 29 percent greater chance of survival over the next 15 years, compared to the group who tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study showed no improvement in survival among post-surgery patients, according to Blackstone, this is a reassuring result for people with a BMI under 35 who are interested in these procedures.
“It is here that this work is critical, because it states that surgery is safer in the lower BMI group,” without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, he says.
Blackstone also argues that people and their doctors should start taking weight seriously after a patient’s BMI drops between 27 and 30.
“I think we’ve waited too long to let people know the gravity of the situation,” he says.
