In the event of bankruptcy, insurance companies are required to pay their clients’ claims in full.
Insurance companies should pay clients’ claims in the event of the travel agency’s bankruptcy in full.
This was decided on Wednesday by the Chamber of Deputies, when it approved a revised amendment to the Law on Business Conditions in Tourism.
Travel agencies will be able to replace bankruptcy insurance with a bank guarantee, according to a draft heading to the Senate.
Insurance companies do not agree with the obligation to pay clients’ claims even above the agreed limit.
The Ministry of Regional Development insists on the adjustment, argues for consumer protection.
Insurance companies have already threatened to stop insuring travel agencies against bankruptcy if the amendment goes into effect.
The proposal has also been criticized by travel agencies.
Without insurance, they will either have to leave or go abroad.
Regional Development Minister Karla <0xC5><0xA0>lechtová (for ANO) pointed out that cases where insurance companies did not pay full compensation are not Eurocomform.
She drew attention to this year’s decision of the Constitutional Court, which confirmed that the client is entitled to a full refund regardless of the insurance limit.
Insurance companies will receive enough information about the management of travel agencies and will be able to determine the right limit, said <0xC5><0xA0>lechtová.
"We appreciate the effort to increase consumer protection, but it must have such a limit to be feasible," said Miroslav Kalousek, vice-chairman of TOP 09.
According to him, the bank guarantee will not work, because no one will give it unlimited.
"Travel agencies will have to close down or move abroad," Kalousek warned.
Member of the Presidium of the Association of Czech Travel Agencies Tomio Okamura (SPD) disagreed with Kalousek’s concerns based on a survey among members of the Central Committee.
"Stop lobbying us insurance companies," he said.
According to him, Okamura does not consider the statements of the insurance companies to be relevant, and there is no official written statement of the insurance companies in this sense.
But they are investigating whether travel agencies will co-pay, which Okamura says is not a problem.
Jana Fischerová (ODS) also warned about the provision, referring to the opinion of the competitive Association of Travel Agencies of the Czech Republic, and her party colleague Petr Bendl, who spoke about the lubrication of the stairs to Czech travel agencies.
According to Fischer, travel agencies will not be able to negotiate insurance.
"Consumer protection works," Fischer said.
Her motion for the removal of the disputed passage was not approved by the House.
Vojt<0xC4><0x9B>ch Filip (KS<0xC4><0x8C>M) did not come with a proposal to return the draft to the committee because of the alleged violation of the Civil Code.
Philip warned about travel agencies, which, according to him, can threaten consumers.
The rapporteur of the draft, Martina Berdychová (ANO), withdrew her proposal, which would limit the liability of insurance companies in cases where they could not know that insurance coverage would not cover the entire risk, in view of the ruling of the Constitutional Court.
The amendment will not initially propose a minimum insurance limit of $4 million for travel agencies offering air travel and a limit of $1 million for offices selling, for example, bus tours.
The limit will remain at 30 percent of the planned revenues from the sale of tours.
However, the insurance coverage limit will have to be such as to cover all customer claims in the event of the travel agency’s bankruptcy.
Even after the amendments, the standard stipulates that travel agencies will have to indicate which travel agency organizes the tour for the sold tours.
Travel agencies will have to provide insurance companies with, among other things, data on the economy and the number of trips before concluding the contract.
The approved amendment of the Public Administration Committee also provides for further regular information of insurance companies.
Every month, travel agents will have to provide them with data on the number of passengers and sold tours, on the total price of sold tours and on the amount of advances and sales for tours and for vouchers.
If the Ministry of Regional Development finds that the travel agency has failed to fulfil any of its legal obligations towards the insurance company, it will call on it to remedy the problem or may prohibit it from entering into new contracts in the event that the breach of the obligation could endanger the interests of customers.
The amendment is also intended to restructure the financing of the mountain service.
The Ministry of Regional Development will determine the amount of the subsidy to the mountain service on the basis of its request, which it will apply each year until the end of April for the next year.
The application will include a report on the use of state money in the past year, a financial plan of expenditure and a outlook for the next two years.
According to the association, however, the lawmaker has not figured out what will happen if the insurance company terminates the CK contract.
It will not be allowed to organize tours and clients who bought the trip before the insurance was cancelled will lose it, according to the association.
In this case, the CC will suffer a significant loss and may even go bankrupt, although its management was in good shape.
One of the ways in which travel agencies can cope with such a situation will be to sue the state for compensation.
Another option will be to go abroad and use much softer conditions abroad, and then we will act only as agencies on our market, said the vice-chairman of the association Jan Pape<0xC5><0xBE>.
According to him, the draft amendment also contains the institute of bank guarantee, but so thoughtlessly that it cannot be implemented in practice at all, because the bank guarantee cannot sound to an unlimited amount.
In addition, according to the association, the change in the current practice is de facto unnecessary.
The whole law will have to be revised again within two years in view of the new EU directive.
A total of 942 active travel insurance companies are currently operating on the Czech market.
So far this year, only three KCs have closed their operations.
Domestic travel agencies sell annually tours worth about twenty billion CZK.
