"The federal states also support the German government in promoting a fair distribution of the weight of the refugee crisis to European countries," Merkel said.
Dietmar Woidke, the state prime minister of Brandenburg, said at a press conference that he expected real solidarity from all EU states.
The distribution of refugees in the EU on the basis of quotas has long been rejected, among other things, by the Czech Republic.
Merkel and Woidke also spoke in favour of speeding up asylum proceedings in Germany.
People need to know as soon as possible if they have a chance to stay here.
It is also necessary for the authorities to be able to start integrating foreigners more quickly, the Prime Minister of Brandenburg said.
According to him, most of the money that Germany spends on the care of refugees should be used for the integration of those who have a chance to obtain asylum.
More teachers will be needed for refugees to master German.
This is a great challenge for our country, but I believe that if we manage to integrate refugees, they can become a benefit for us, he said.
