Xi calls for opening up the economy to the wider world
It is necessary to open the economy to the wider world to boost growth, President Xi Jinping told a group tasked with governance reform on Tuesday.
"China should engage in attracting foreign investment and expertise and improve open policies," he said about the 16th meeting of the central group leader to deepen overall reform.
Promoting opening-up in nascent reforms will give a new impetus and vitality, as well as provide new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The Steering Group adopted a number of directives, including a negative list of regulatory market access, the easing of border control policies, support for state-owned enterprises (SOEs) to absorb private capital and the reorganisation of the registration resident system.
The statement states that a negative list will be drawn up identifying sectors and enterprises that are outside the investment limits.
This system will be gradually tested and improved through test programmes.
This step is significant because it will give the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensuring a legal business environment and making the market more open, the statement said.
The government will also loosen controls on the powers it delegates to companies and make sure the firms themselves decide how to run their businesses.
The statement also said that China will allow border areas to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to support regional growth.
In an effort to open up the state-controlled sector, more areas will be opened up to private investment.
“The government will not change its policy on foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of companies that are financed from abroad and will provide them with better services,” the statement said.
In addition, it will be easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or a "green card", thanks to the optimization of requirements and the simplification of the application process.
Ensuring the rights of lawyers to practice and develop professional judges and prosecutors was also discussed at the meeting.
The meeting was also attended by Premier Li Keqiang and leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, according to a statement issued after the meeting.
In the Karlovy Vary Region, new beds may be created.
According to the Deputy Governor of the Karlovy Vary Region, Jakub Pánik (<0xC4><0x8C>SSD), the current capacity of bed departments of two regional hospitals and two private hospitals in the region is sufficient and partial adjustments should be made on the basis of an agreement between the departments of individual hospitals.
However, there are also opportunities to expand care in the region.
For example, in the department of surgical departments, one-day surgery centers could be established, where, according to the set concept, surgical procedures would be performed that do not require hospitalization for more than 24 hours.
It is not yet clear in which specific hospitals the one-day surgery facilities should be.
The skin department of the Karlovy Vary hospital could, in turn, create a laser center with the possibility of using laser technology for skin diseases.
The concept also recommended the creation of an apical center that would care for patients with brain disabilities who are in a vegetative state.
Such a center should be established centrally and should be an integral part of the anesthesiological-resuscitation department.
There is also the possibility of concentrating such a facility in the Ostrov hospital, where similar care already exists.
Another bed capacity, which appears to be insufficient in the Karlovy Vary Region, are the beds of follow-up care, especially the beds of the Long-Term Care (LDN), whose capacity in Nejdek is insufficient and, above all, should be closely related to acute care beds.
Part of this device should function as a rehabilitation bed and part as a classic LDN bed, recommends the concept.
As he points out, the beds of follow-up care are missing mainly in the Karlovy Vary hospital.
There you can use the abandoned buildings after centralization.
Last but not least, in the Karlovy Vary Region, social health beds with a focus on the treatment of Alzheimer's disease are absent.
There is a shortage of such beds throughout the republic, so it could also serve for other regions as the so-called Alzheimer's Center.
According to the recommendation, hospitals should also prepare for the introduction of so-called follow-up beds, to which funds from European subsidies will be released.
"These are beds that will follow the fields of superspecialized care and will create a space for the translation of patients after surgery, for example, after cardiac surgery, neurosurgery, transplantation or other surgery," describes the regional concept of in-patient care.
New services could also be offered in the field of psychiatric care.
